{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477793"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:05:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14717"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14717","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14717"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.04,0.09,0.21,0.54]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7410"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58149"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7410","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7410"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14717"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43608"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"913"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18084"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43941"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58149"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-month-old girl presents to the General Practice clinic for routine immunisations. Her parent mentions receiving a letter about positive hepatitis C serology during pregnancy. The baby was born at term via normal vaginal delivery with no complications. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is feeding well and gaining weight appropriately.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is no jaundice, hepatomegaly, or other abnormal findings. Blood tests reveal alanine aminotransferase 45 U/L (10-40) and positive hepatitis C antibody.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Commence antiviral therapy","Liver ultrasound","No further follow-up required","Refer to paediatric gastroenterologist","Repeat hepatitis C antibody testing at 18 months of age"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis infant has been exposed to hepatitis C virus through vertical transmission from her mother. Maternal antibodies can persist in infants for up to 18 months, making hepatitis C antibody testing unreliable before this age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat hepatitis C antibody testing at 18 months\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This allows time for maternal antibodies to clear and provides a more accurate assessment of the infant\u0027s true infection status. If antibodies persist beyond 18 months, this indicates chronic infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntiviral therapy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this age. Given the high rate of spontaneous clearance in infancy (20-45% in the first two years), treatment is typically deferred until the child is older and chronic infection is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely indicated in asymptomatic infants with possible hepatitis C infection. The liver enzyme elevation is mild and likely transient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to a paediatric gastroenterologist\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were concerning features such as significant liver dysfunction, but this infant is well with only mildly elevated liver enzymes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo further follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as this infant requires monitoring to determine their infection status. Regular clinical review and repeat testing are essential components of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMost children with chronic hepatitis C infection remain asymptomatic with normal or mildly elevated liver enzymes. The disease typically progresses slowly, with complications such as cirrhosis being rare in childhood. Regular monitoring allows for early detection of any complications and ensures appropriate timing of treatment if needed.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hepatitis C virus infection acquired in infancy has a 20-45% chance of spontaneous clearance in the first two years of life.","Children with chronic hepatitis C are usually asymptomatic but may have elevated liver enzymes that normalize over time.","Vertical transmission is the most common route of hepatitis C infection in children."],"references":["Jarasvaraparn C, Hartley C, Karnsakul W. Updated Clinical Guidelines on the Management of Hepatitis C Infection in Children. Pathogens. 2024 Feb 16;13(2):180. doi: 10.3390/pathogens13020180. PMID: 38392918; PMCID: PMC10891648."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43608"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14717"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"43608","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/43608"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-29T14:28:21+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-29T14:29:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7410"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58149"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"htt